@NODE "INTRO" "Introduction"
@NEXT "FEAT"
@PREV "DISC"

                            @{u}@{b}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

     @{fg shine}MegaStat@{fg text} is a cross between EchoStat by  Phil  O'Malley  and
     AreaStat  by  Brian Jacobson, except with many more features
     added. My thanks should  go  to  both  Phil  and  Brian  for
     excellent  scripts,  without  which  I  wouldn't have a clue
     where to start writing my own!

     @{i}Why did I do it?@{ui} The answer is simple - the main  reason  is
     that EchoStat has been updated, but only for use on OS/2 for
     the PC. The other reason is that a PC  owning  'gloater'  in
     one  of  the echos I take said how good his stats looks, and
     looking at the available Amiga ones I saw what he meant. Not
     wanting to be outdone by a PC user, and having the chance to
     test my newly found Arexx programming skills I  thought  I'd
     have a bash.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FEAT" "Feature List"
@NEXT "FILES"
@PREV "INTRO"

                        @{u}@{b}MegaStat Features@{uu}@{ub}


     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} MegaStat has two ways of message  sorting,  one  where  by
       Spot  saves  out  every  message, gaining more information
       (Average message size, quote ratios  etc.)  but  lacks  in
       speed.  Alternatively  MegaStat  just  scans the header is
       much faster!

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Tables produced include:

          @{b}    * Writer Table
              * Receiver Table
              * Quote Blacklist Table
              * Subjects Table
              * Tearline Table
              * Node Traffic Table
              * Hourly Usage Graph
              * Daily Usage Graph
          @{ub}
     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Ability to disable/enable any of the tables via config  or
       on every use of the script.

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Period of message scan for inclusion in  the  stat  tables
       can     be     selected     from     pre-defined     menus
       (Week/Fortnight/Month), alternatively the user can  define
       start  and  finish dates, or select for ALL the message to
       be processed.

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} "Multiple" stats allow you to select more than  one  area,
       all treated as single area and a MegaStat message produced
       for each one. Handy for those that produce stats for  more
       than one area!

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} "Joint" stats allow you to select more than one  area  and
       treat  all the messages in these areas as one area (unlike
       the Multiple Stat option) and  provide  a  large  combined
       stat message.

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Usenet ":" quoting is treated identical to  normal Fidonet
       standard quoting (">").

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Has extensive  command  line  options,  making  automation
       easy. Want to use a cron program to create large stats for
       your areas while in bed? MegaStat allows you  to  do  this
       with no user intervention at all!

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Logs are produced as a  file  and/or  a  message  in  Spot
       depending  on  user preference. Use these to check if your
       stat went according to how you wanted it, if  you  weren't
       there.

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Config file for ease of use and full automation of certain
       aspects of MegaStat.

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} Plus many other advantages  over  other  scripts  such  as
       EchoStat and AreaStat...
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FILES" "Files needed by MegaStat"
@NEXT "INST"
@PREV "FEAT"

                 @{u}@{b}Files needed by MegaStat to run@{uu}@{ub}


     @{b}Libraries:@{ub}

      libs:traplist.library
      libs:rexxsupport.library


     @{b}Commands:@{ub}

      c:copy
      c:delete


     You will also require a  nodelist  that  should  be  updated
     every  week. If the nodelist is not recent enough to contain
     newer bulletin boards you will most  likely  get  a  lot  of
     unknown addresses in the tables MegaStat produces.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "INST" "Installing MegaStat.spot"
@NEXT "CONFIG"
@PREV "FILES"

                 @{u}@{b}How to install and run MegaStat@{ub}@{uu}


     Installing MegaStat is easy, all that is required is to copy
     the   MegaStat.spot  script  from  this  archive  into  your
     @{b}rexx:spot/@{ub} directory.

     After doing this you must change  the  directory  where  the
     prefs  file  is  to  go,  if  you  need  to.  The default is
     @{b}"mail:MegaStat.cfg"@{ub} so that should suit  everybody,  without
     having  to  adapt  the  script. If you want to use the prefs
     file from elsewhere you must edit  the  line  early  in  the
     MegaStat.spot script that looks like this:

     @{fg shine}
     config          = "Mail:MegaStat.cfg"
     @{fg text}

     Also, if you want to use MegaStat from shell via the command
     line (See @{"Command Line Options" LINK "CLI"}) then you also need to change
     the path and file to invoke Spot if its not running.  Change
     the line in the script that looks like this:

     @{fg shine}
     spot_path       = "mail:spot/spot"
     @{fg text}

     Then simply add the script to  your  Arexx  menu  so  it  is
     easily accessible, using the Settings/Arexx menu in Spot.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CONFIG" "Configuring MegaStat.spot"
@NEXT "RUN"
@PREV "INST"

                      @{b}@{u}Configuring the script@{uu}@{ub}

     Due to the many features that MegaStat  contains,  it  would
     have been very difficult to provide the user with an easy to
     use script. For this reason I decided to implement a  simple
     prefs file for use with MegaStat. This prefs file contains a
     lot of defaults specific to  the  user  and  can  easily  be
     changed via any ASCII editor.

     The prefs file for MegaStat is automatically created by  the
     script  when  you first run it. When you do run MegaStat you
     will be faced by a lot of requesters in order to create  the
     prefs  file  for  you.  These  include  values for excessive
     quoting ratio, new topic content,  table  length  and  which
     tables  to  include.  All these are described below so it is
     important  you  read  the  description  to  know   what   is
     happening!

     For most of the requesters you have  the  option  to  "@{fg shine}SKIP@{fg text}"
     saving  the  setting into the megastat.cfg file. This option
     will be asked  every  time  you  run  MegaStat  (unless  you
     override  it  with  the  CLI  options)  in  case you require
     different options when you produce stats.

     Don't worry though, none of the options are permenant as you
     can  always  edit the prefs file yourself and change it (See
     @{"Example Prefs File" LINK "EPF"}).



     @{u}@{b}Excessive Quote Ratio@{uu}@{ub}

     The Excessive Quote Ratio value is the number  you  wish  to
     use as the maximum a user can quote in an echo without being
     deemed to be "over-quoting". If their average quote ratio is
     greater  than  the  chosen limit (defaults to 55%) then they
     are marked in that stat table as quoting too much!

     Suggested value: @{fg shine}55@{fg text}


     @{u}@{b}New Topic Content@{uu}@{ub}

     The New Topic Content value is the number you wish to use as
     the  minimum  a  topic/subject  in  an  echo is deemed to be
     "wasting bandwidth" and so contains text which is  old  hat.
     If  the  average  quote  ratio is less than the chosen limit
     (defaults to 30%), meaning in average each  message  in  the
     thread  contains  only 30% new text then it is marked in the
     stat table as wasting  too  much  bandwidth  and  should  be
     killed.

     Suggested value: @{fg shine}30@{fg text}


     @{u}@{b}Table Length@{uu}@{ub}

     Here MegaStat allows you to  choose  the  number  of  people
     counted  in  the  stat table, ie whether you want a table of
     the Top 10 users or a table of the Top 1000 users! If  there
     is  not  enough  users  in  the echo to make up the required
     table length then the table will be cut short. If you  would
     like  to  have  @{b}all@{ub} the user/subjects/nodes/tearlines (etc.)
     displayed in the tables then you can type "@{fg shine}0@{fg text}" (zero).

     Requirments will be different depending on  the  period  the
     stat  is  to  cover and the size of an echo. For instance it
     would be silly to use a table of 20 for a 1 week stat period
     in an echo with a small traffic flow!

     @{b}Remember:@{ub}  you  can  type  "@{fg shine}SKIP@{fg text}"  and  use  this requester
     everytime you produce a stat.

     Suggested value: @{fg shine}10@{fg text}


     @{u}@{b}Quote Ratio and Average Size@{uu}@{ub}

     There  are  two  main  differences  between   AreaStat   and
     EchoStat.  That  is  speed.  AreaStat only contains the most
     basic of information  while  EchoStat  also  contains  quote
     ratios.  To  do this, Spot is made to save out every message
     to be assessed and so can take a very  long  time!  MegaStat
     therefore  allows  you  to do simple stats without the quote
     ratio and the average message size included in the tables.

     @{b}Note:@{ub} If you select "@{fg shine}NO@{fg text}" on this requester you will  not  be
     able  to  produce  the Tearline table or the Quote Blacklist
     table. Both these tables need information that is taken when
     the message is saved out so obviously can't be produced.

     Although it takes a long time with the  messages  saved,  it
     makes the stats much more nicer :)

     Suggested: @{fg shine}SKIP@{fg text}


     @{u}@{b}Logging@{uu}@{ub}

     MegaStat allows you to create a  log  in  two  manners.  The
     first  is a @{b}Log File@{ub}, saved out to a user-defined directory.
     The second is a @{b}Log Message@{ub} saved out to a user-defined area
     -  a  good idea is to save it out to a "keep" area that does
     not get exported from Spot.

     You can of course use both options, saving out to file,  and
     as a message.

     (See @{"Example Log File" LINK "ELF"})

     Suggested: @{fg shine}Both@{fg text}


     @{u}@{b}Period of Message Scan@{uu}@{ub}

     Lets you select the time period that should  be  scanned  to
     produce  the  stat.  Lets you select a month, a fortnight, a
     week or all the messages in the area.

     If you use "@{fg shine}SKIP@{fg text}" on this requester, when you  run  MegaStat
     again  it will also have another option - user-defined start
     and end dates. Here you can select your own period,  but  it
     @{b}must@{ub} be entered in the format DD.MM.YYYY!

     Suggested: @{fg shine}SKIP@{fg text}


     @{u}@{b}Tables@{uu}@{ub}

     The next 8 requesters are all concerned  with  which  tables
     are  to  be  produced.  MegaStat  allows  you to disable the
     output of any of the  tables  if  you  think  they  are  not
     required for the area (for example, if it is a local area to
     your board and only contains users with one origin node  you
     would disable the @{i}Node Traffic Table@{ui}).

     Suggested: @{b}All@{ub} tables as "@{fg shine}YES@{fg text}".


     @{u}@{b}Default Areas/Multiple Areas@{uu}@{ub}

     The next requester (and listview) allows you to select  some
     default  echos  that  can  be  scanned with the click of one
     button. Say if you produce stat tables  for  more  than  one
     echo,  instead  of  selecting one echo and running MegaStat,
     waiting for it finish and then doing the same for the other,
     instead you select the two areas here (pressing Cancel after
     the second) and use the "@{b}MULTIPLE@{ub}" option  in  MegaStat.  It
     will  create  the stats for both areas without you having to
     do anything else.

     This is extemely useful if you produce stats for  a  lot  of
     areas,  and can be used in conjunction with the command line
     options.

     If you don't want to select any, simply press  "@{fg shine}CANCEL@{fg text}",  if
     you  do  want  to  select  a/some  echo(s)  then keep double
     clicking on the areas required until you have  finished  and
     then press "@{fg shine}CANCEL@{fg text}" to save them.

     (See @{"Multiple Areas" LINK "RUN"})


     @{u}@{b}Joint Areas@{uu}@{ub}

     This is a fantastic feature only available in @{b}MegaStat@{ub}! When
     you  select  a @{b}Joint Stat@{ub} it goes through the areas you have
     saved in your prefs like normal but treats all the areas  as
     one  giant echo, producing a single stat for them. This is a
     nice feature if you want to create a large stat for a  small
     network, or a stat of all your BBS's local areas.

     Simple select the default areas you want as explained in the
     @{i}Multiple Areas@{ui} part.

     (See @{"Joint Areas" LINK "RUN"})



     There you go! You  have  finished  creating  the  preference
     file.  It may seem like a lot to take in but I assure you it
     is worthwhile if you want to get the best out of the script.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RUN" "Running and using MegaStat"
@PREV "CONFIG"
@NEXT "EPF"

             @{u}@{b}Running MegaStat (For the second time)@{ub}@{uu}

     Once you have setup the preferences to  suit  you,  you  can
     then  run  the  script  again  to  enable you to create some
     stats.

     If you are producing a stat for a @{b}single@{ub}  area,  first  goto
     that  area,  leaving  it  on  either  the  message list, the
     message screen or the arealist in  Spot.  You  can  the  run
     MegaStat.spot.  If  you  are  doing a @{b}Multiple@{ub} or @{b}Joint Stat@{ub}
     then it doesn't matter where you are.

     You will be first greeted by the main menu, with options  to
     produce  a  simple  "@{fg shine}STAT@{fg text}",  a  "@{fg shine}MULTIPLE@{fg text}" stat or a "@{fg shine}JOINT@{fg text}"
     stat.

     After selecting one of the above, you will be  requested  to
     select  options  from  the  requesters  you  SKIP'ed  in the
     @{"Configuration" LINK "CONFIG"} section. Then one of three things will happen:

     Selecting a simple @{b}STAT@{ub} will create a stat for the area  you
     are  currently  in,  write  the  message,  and write the log
     file/message if needed. It will then return to the  Arealist
     in Spot.

     Selecting a @{b}MULTIPLE@{ub} stat will bring up another menu for you
     to either use the default echos as in the prefs file, or the
     user can select some alternatives. Once done, MegaStat  will
     go  through each echo producing stats for each, then produce
     the logs if needed. It will then return to the Arealist.

     Selecting a @{b}JOINT@{ub} stat will bring up another menu, the  same
     as the multiple stat one. When it has finished going through
     all the area reading the values from the messages,  it  will
     bring up a listview requestor asking for an area to post the
     stat in. After selecting one, you can keep  selecting  areas
     to  post the stat into, until you press cancel. The log will
     then be produced and MegaStat returns to the Arealist.

     Also available in both the Joint and Multiple Stat sub-menus
     are  the options to use a @{b}Pattern@{ub} when creating a stat. This
     is a standard prefix of echos that you would like to scan  -
     ie  all  my boss' local areas start with the prefix "@{fg shine}LOCAL@{fg text}",
     so instead of writing/selecting each echo (over 28) then you
     would  just  type  "@{fg shine}LOCAL@{fg text}"  in  the  requester that pops up.
     Another example is if you wanted to do a stat  of  all  your
     netmail areas, in Spot they all have the areatag of "@{fg shine}NET@{fg text}".


     There you have it. Simple eh? ;)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "EPF" "Example Prefs File"
@PREV "RUN"
@NEXT "ELF"

     Here is my current prefs file, with the comments cut out  so
     I can explain how/what you can change. The white text (on my
     system anyway!) is the actual line of the config file:

     (@{b}Note:@{ub} the first word in UPPERCASE is the keyword  and  must
     be included! For example "NAME")


      @{fg shine}NAME "Paul Nuzzo"@{fg text}

     Your name; should be exactly  like  the  one  in  your  Spot
     settings (as it is taken from there!).


      @{fg shine}LOGFILE mail:Logs/@{fg text}

     The path to your  log  file,  including  trailing  colon  of
     slash. If you do not wish to have a log file creates use the
     option @{b}NO@{ub}, e.g. "LOGFILE NO"


      @{fg shine}LOGECHO KEEP_ECHO@{fg text}

     The echo to keep the log message. Again, use the option NO
     if you do not want to keep a log message.


      @{fg shine}TABLELEN 10@{fg text}

     The number  of  entries  you  want  per  table.  Use  0  for
     unlimited  entries  and  SKIP  to  be  asked  this  question
     everytime.


      @{fg shine}DATE SKIP@{fg text}

     The  period  for  the   stat   to   be   covered.   Can   be
     WEEK/FORTNIGHT/MONTH/SKIP or 0 for all messages in the area.


      @{fg shine}WRITERS YES
      RECEIVERS YES
      SUBJECTS YES
      TEARLINES YES
      NODES YES
      QUOTERS YES
      DAYSTAT YES
      TIMESTAT YES        @{fg text}

     Select which tables you would like.  YES  if  you  want  the
     table,  NO  if  you  don't and SKIP to be asked the question
     every time.


      @{fg shine}SIZEQUOTE SKIP@{fg text}

     Select whether you would like to save out every message, and
     so  include  the quote ratio and average message size in the
     tables.


      @{fg shine}XSQUOTE 55@{fg text}

     The Excessive Quote Ratio value, see  configuration  section
     for more detail.


      @{fg shine}NEWTOPIC 30@{fg text}

     The New Topic Content value, see configuration  section  for
     more detail.


      @{fg shine}AREA LOCALSOFTWARE@{fg text}

     A MULTIPLE area default echo. This area will be scanned when
     you  select  a MULTIPLE stat from the main menu. You can add
     as many areas as you want, using "AREA <areatag>".


      @{fg shine}MULTIAREA SPOT
      MULTIAREA SPOT_AMY@{fg text}

     Two JOINT area echos. These will be scanned when you  select
     JOINT  stat  from  the main menu and a large joint echo stat
     message will be created. Again, you can add more echos using
     "MULTIAREA <areatag>"

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ELF" "Example Log File"
@PREV "EPF"
@NEXT "CLI"

     This is an example of one  of  the  log  files  produced  by
     MegaStat:

<--- >8 Snip 8< --->

Saturday 11 Nov 1995:
19:17:07 Produced stats for LOCALTHATBBS
19:17:07 Produced stats for LOCALTHISBBS
19:17:07 Period : 05 Nov 1995 - 11 Nov 1995 : 35 messages processed in total.
19:17:07 Flags: WRQSNTHD
19:17:07 Time Taken : 22.66
19:17:07 Error: Quote Blacklist Table - Quote Ratios and Msg Size wasn't selected
19:17:07 Error: Tearline Table - Quote Ratios and Msg Size wasn't selected

<--- >8 Snip 8< --->

     We should take note of a few things:


      @{fg shine}19:17:07 Flags: WRQSNTHD@{fg text}

     Each letter of the text "WRQSNTHD" tells you which table was
     used  in  the stat. If a table wasn't used, then a dash, "-"
     would be used instead.

     Key:

         W = Writer Table
         R = Receiver Table
         Q = Quote Blacklist Table
         S = Subject Table
         N = Node Traffic Table
         T = Tearline Table
         H = Hourly Graph
         D = Daily Graph


     Also the lines stating an error has occured, with the  Quote
     Blacklist  and  the  Tearline tables is due to not using the
     slow method of saving out every message in the echo. If  the
     Tearline  and  Quote  Blacklist tables were selected as "NO"
     then the errors would not have  occured.  The  message  will
     still  be  produced though, just without those tables that's
     all!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CLI" "Command Line Options for MegaStat"
@PREV "ELF"
@NEXT "BUGS"

               @{b}@{u}Using MegaStat via the command line@{ub}@{uu}

     One of MegaStat's excellent features is the ability  to  run
     the  script  from  the  command  line.  Running  it from the
     command line can make it run in exactly the same way as  you
     run  the  script  from Spot's menus, but you can also run it
     silently without the need to click on any menus.

     For this reason, MegaStat is  ideal  for  use  with  a  Cron
     utility  which  could  run the script at night while you are
     sound asleep in your bed. Espcially useful  for  those  long
     stat  sessions  like mine where I need to save out over 3000
     messages to produce a stat!

     Type "rx rexx:spot/MegaStat.spot ?" in  the  CLI  to  get  a
     usage template of the script:


      @{b}6. Rexx:spot> rx megastat.spot ?@{ub}
      @{i}MegaStat v1.0
      Usage: rx MegaStat.spot [SUPPRESS] [FLAGS <WRQSTNHD>]
      [SAVE <YES/NO>] [DATE <WEEK/FORTNIGHT/MONTH/ALL>]
      [TABLE <length>] [MULTIPLE] [JOINT <Area to post>]
      [STAT <Areatag>]@{ui}


     The keywords/options are as follows:

     Arguments for the keywords are in angled brackets (@{b}< and >@{ub}).

     @{fg shine}[SUPPRESS]@{fg text} - Suppresses   all   the   requesters    normally
                  displayed.  If  you don't select otherwise, all
                  preference requesters that were SKIP'ed will be
                  defaulted to NO. Therefore if you have the date
                  requester to come up everytime you run MegaStat
                  you  need  to  set  the  date  the DATE keyword
                  below.

     @{fg shine}[FLAGS <WRQSTNHD>]@{fg text} - This enables you to select which tables
                  to include if you have them selected as  "SKIP"
                  in  the prefs file.  See  example log file  for
                  info on the flags.

     @{fg shine}[SAVE <YES/NO>]@{fg text} - Enables you to switch saving  message out,
                  or not for speed.  Will default to "NO"  if you
                  have it as SKIP in the prefs file.

     @{fg shine}[DATE <WEEK/FORTNIGHT/MONTH/ALL>]@{fg text} - Select the date you wish
                  to  scan for messages.  Must be defined  if you
                  have this as "SKIP" in the prefs file.

     @{fg shine}[TABLE <length>]@{fg text} - Lets  you  define the  length of all  the
                  tables that are created. 0 for unlimited.

     @{fg shine}[MULTIPLE]
     [JOINT <area to post in>]
     [STAT <areatag>]@{fg text} - You must select one of these in order  to
                  do the stat if you have SUPPRESS used. MULTIPLE
                  just emulates  doing a  Multiple stat from  the
                  main  menu,  JOINT does a  Joint stat,  and you
                  have  to provide  an area  for the  stat to  be
                  posted to  after the  JOINT keyword.  STAT just
                  does a normal single echo stat - the  area that
                  is scanned  for  the stat  is written after the
                  STAT keyword.



     @{b}@{u}Examples@{ub}@{uu}

      @{i}rx megastat.spot SUPPRESS SAVE YES DATE WEEK STAT SPOT@{ui}

     Will write a single area stat  in  the  echo  "SPOT",  using
     quote  ratio  and  average  message size for a period of one
     week. No requesters will pop up due to the SUPPRESS keyword,
     and all tables selected in the prefs file will be created.


      @{i}rx megastat.spot SUPPRESS FLAGS WRN SAVE NO DATE ALL @{ui}@{b}->@{ub}@{i}
       JOINT SPOT@{ui}

     Will write a Joint stat scanning all the echos in  the  list
     from the prefs file, and save it into the area SPOT. It will
     go though all the message, not  saving  them  just  grabbing
     info from the headers. MegaStat would create tables selected
     as YES from the prefs file, and would  also  create  Writer,
     Receiver  and Node Traffic tables if not already selected as
     YES (FLAGS WRN).

@ENDNODE


@NODE "BUGS" "Known bugs and how to report a bug"
@PREV "CLI"
@NEXT "HIST"

                           @{u}@{b}Known Bugs@{ub}@{uu}

     Here are some bugs I know about, but are either not my fault
     and so can't be helped, or require too much code to work
     around in this version:

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} If a message is dated pre-1978 then there  is  no  way  of
       finding  out  the day it was written on due to a "feature"
       of the OS/clock using date() command in Arexx. I've used a
       kludge  so  it doesn't bomb out though, by making the year
       equal to 1978. Shouldn't be a  prob,  or  wouldn't  be  if
       people kept their clocks dated correctly ;)

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} MegaStat uses the information from the last message  of  a
       user  -  so  if a person changes nodes in between stats it
       will come up as the new node they are  at.  Same  for  the
       tearline etc.

     @{fg shine}o@{fg text} If a person uses a TO:  header  of  something  like  "John
       Smith/Joe  Bloggs" then it will turn up as "John Smith/joe
       Bloggs" due to the way I have to convert  words  to  lower
       case and convert the initials upto uppercase afterwards.


                 @{u}@{b}What to do when you find a bug@{ub}@{uu}

    In the unlikely event you find  a  bug,  please  keep  it  to
    yourself and don't let anyone know. Even me.

    Only joking! :)

    If you find a bug (hopefully not!) please report  it  to  me,
    and  if  I  can  I will fix it for another version. Thanks in
    advance for trying the script out!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "HIST" "History of MegaStat"
